1000 AI agents, 5000 rounds, one commodity. Margin drops from 30% to 2%. Four strategies go extinct, two split the market. A reproducible simulation consistently generating five stylized facts of real financial markets. Not a forecast. Not a thought experiment. An artifact runnable on a single GPU.

Santa Fe Institute Artificial Stock Market (Arthur, Holland, LeBaron, Palmer, Taylor, 1997) set the paradigm: 100-1000 agents with simple rules produce complex market behavior. 1990s models required supercomputers. In 2026, the open-source stack runs 100K agents in real-time on one GPU. Simulators stopped being academic curiosities. Companies spin them up before entering commodity markets. Prop-trading desks use them as a validation gate. The gap between "run a stress test" and "blindly trust a business plan" gets measured in margin points that no longer exist.

## Double-auction with profit feedback

N agents trade one commodity on a double-auction market. Each agent receives an initial endowment of goods and cash, a private value (individual utility estimate), a bid/ask strategy, and a profit feedback loop for adaptation.

Not a model of the entire economy. A laboratory experiment for testing market microstructure hypotheses. Real economies have millions of participants, regulatory shocks, black swans, information asymmetry. The simulator fixes assumptions and shows what happens under them. Not "what will happen." Rather "what could happen, if."

## Five regularities that emerge uninvited

After 10K+ rounds, the simulation consistently reproduces five stylized facts of real financial markets:

| Regularity | Essence | Mechanism in simulator |
|---|---|---|
| Fat tails in return distributions | Extreme price movements occur more often than normal distribution predicts | Emerges with > 200 agents running different strategies |
| Volatility clustering | High-volatility periods group together | Appears when learning agents (ZIP, GDX) are present |
| Long memory in order flow | Bid-ask spreads and volumes are autocorrelated over 50-100 rounds | Feedback loop: agents react to their own signals |
| Power-law wealth distribution | The rich get richer, the poor get poorer (Pareto) | Amplified by different risk-aversion profiles |
| Flash crashes | Sudden drops of 3-10% within 1-3 rounds | Triggered by "panic" among learning agents |

These patterns are not the result of specially tuned rules. They emerge from interactions among agents with simple strategies. Emergent complexity invisible in models with 5-10 agents.

