## Who survives to round 5000

Series of runs: 1000 agents, equal split across five strategies, 5000 rounds.

```
Round   0:    ZI=200  ZIP=200  GDX=200  Pure-Aggr=200  Conservative=200
Round 200:    ZI=80   ZIP=380  GDX=290  Pure-Aggr=20   Conservative=230
Round 500:    ZI=15   ZIP=420  GDX=350  Pure-Aggr=0    Conservative=215
Round 2000:   ZI=2    ZIP=480  GDX=420  Pure-Aggr=0    Conservative=98
Round 5000:   ZI=0    ZIP=520  GDX=410  Pure-Aggr=0    Conservative=70
```

Pure-aggressive strategies go extinct within 30-50 rounds. Margins compress faster than they can retrain. ZI (Zero Intelligence) die second: no learning loop, no adaptation to shifting microstructure. Conservative strategies shrink but don't vanish. Small predictable profit keeps them in the game. ZIP+GDX capture 93% of the market by round 5000.

Tacit collusion without explicit coordination. In 5-7% of rounds, ZIP+GDX clusters synchronously widen spreads, reproducing the "silent cartel" pattern. No message exchange. Pure emergent coordination from profit feedback.

## The price spiral toward zero

Separate experiment: 200 agents sell an identical commodity, initial margin 30%.

Rounds 1-20: margin fluctuates 25-32%, stable zone. Rounds 20-50: aggressive agents lower asks, margin drops to 15-20%. Rounds 50-150: compression spiral, each round someone cuts the price by 1-2%, others must follow. Rounds 150-300: margin at 2-5%, individual agents trading at zero or negative. Rounds 300-500: mass bankruptcies, 30-50 agents with the lowest cost base survive. Rounds 500+: oligopoly of 5-10 agents, margin recovers to 15-25%.

Price wars are not market failure. Normal state during commoditization. Trying to "hold prices" through tacit agreements loses to agents that refuse to play along. One way out: differentiation. Exit the commodity segment.

